The word is not found in any other writer except in a fragment of Varro. Whatever may be its derivationi, it is worth while to notice that it is nearly always addressed to slaves—only once to a girl and once to an old man—and that it is used by slaves and parasitos, except in three or four instances. It is accompanied with an imperat. mood except in three cases—Capt. 630; Cure. 244, and Men'. ii. 3, 92. None of these passages warrants the expression in the text, which is only explicable on the ground that the parasite is in a passion, and, when railing at the puer, exaggerates in regard to the dimensions of the bread he was in the habit of devouring3 cp.
